{{en-noun}}

# A set of [[clothes]] to be worn together, now especially a man's matching [[jacket]] and [[trousers]] (also [[business suit]] or [[lounge suit]]), or a similar [[outfit]] for a woman.
#* {{quote-book|year=1963|author={{w|Margery Allingham}}|title={{w|The China Governess}}
|chapter=Foreword|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2004261W
|passage=A canister of flour from the kitchen had been thrown at the looking-glass and lay like trampled snow over the remains of a decent blue '''suit''' with the lining ripped out which lay on top of the ruin of a plastic wardrobe.}}
#* {{quote-magazine|date=2013-08-03|volume=408|issue=8847|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21582512-explosion-start-ups-changing-finance-better-revenge-nerds Revenge of the nerds]
|passage=Think of banking today and the image is of grey-'''suit'''ed men in towering skyscrapers. Its future, however, is being shaped in converted warehouses and funky offices in San Francisco, New York and London, where bright young things in jeans and T-shirts huddle around laptops, sipping lattes or munching on free food.}}
#: {{usex|Nick hired a navy-blue '''suit''' for the wedding.|lang=en}}
# {{context|by extension|lang=en}} A single [[garment]] that covers the whole body: [[space suit]], [[boiler suit]], protective suit.
# {{context|pejorative|slang|lang=en}} A person who wears [[matching]] jacket and trousers, especially a [[boss]] or a [[supervisor]].
#: {{usex|Be sure to keep your nose to the grindstone today; the '''suits''' are making a "surprise" visit to this department.|lang=en}}
# A full set of [[armour]].
# {{context|legal|lang=en}} The attempt to gain an end by legal process; a process instituted in a court of law for the recovery of a right or claim; a [[lawsuit]].
#: {{usex|If you take my advice, you'll file '''suit''' against him immediately.|lang=en}}
# {{sense|obsolete}} The act of following or pursuing; [[pursuit]], [[chase]].
# Pursuit of a love-interest; [[wooing]], [[courtship]].
#: ''Rebate your loves, each rival '''suit''' suspend, Till this funereal web my labors end.'' —{{w|Alexander Pope}}.
# The full set of sails required for a ship.
# {{context|card games|lang=en}} Each of the sets of a pack of cards distinguished by color and/or specific emblems, such as the [[spades]], [[hearts]], [[diamonds]]{{,}} or [[clubs]] of traditional Anglo, Hispanic{{,}} and French playing cards.
#: ''To deal and shuffle, to divide and sort Her mingled '''suits''' and sequences.'' — {{w|William Cowper}}.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Regular order; succession.
#: ''Every five and thirty years the same kind and '''suit''' of weather comes again.'' — {{w|Francis Bacon}}.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} The act of suing; the [[pursuit]] of a particular object or goal.
#: ''Thenceforth the '''suit''' of earthly conquest shone.'' — {{w|Edmund Spenser}}.
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} A company of attendants or followers; a [[retinue]].
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} A group of similar or related objects or items considered as a whole; a [[suite]] (of rooms etc.)

